Had a wonderful birthday and “parents meeting parents” dinner here. The food was all delicious and we felt treated super well by our server. Would recommend for a great Italian meal for a special occasion!
Had a tremendous experience here!  One of the best dry aged NY Strips I’ve been very had.  Gluten free options were plentiful, and they were very understanding and cognizant of our food allergies.

Great selection of gluten free foods. The waitress Julie H was very knowledgeable about gluten allergies. There gluten free bread was delicious. I got veal chop and it was the best break I have ever had. I will definitely be coming back.

I was on a trip with family when we decided to stop by for a drink since we were staying across the street. Drinks were delicious, bartender was nice and the manager was great! Sent us back to the hotel with a pizza. There were pool tables, bowling and karaoke was going on in another room. Fun place!

I’m not one to write reviews, but Kings deserves one for how they treat their patrons. My wife, 12 year old daughter, and myself were visiting our other daughter at college and were looking for something to do in back bay. Couldn’t have asked for a more perfect place! We used the arcade, bowled, played pool, ate, and had a blast. We weren’t sure how purchasing a card for the arcade worked, so we asked. The manager himself came over, coached us through it, and even gave us free credits to get us started(which wasn’t necessary or expected at all). The customer service was amazing…from the manager, to our server, to the staff working the counter. It was a pleasure to give them our business and we will definitely be back. Thank you for your hospitality and a great time!

If you're looking for a cool and relaxing place to hang out with your besties (or your SO), King's on Dalton St can't be beat. Walking in, I immediately felt transported back to my arcade days. The dark walls with the occasional neon lights were super-nostalgic.  The GM, Cyle, was super friendly, and personally showed my partner and me to the lounge where we grabbed some high-quality-yet-totally-affordable American food (i.e. burgers, fries, chocolate cake).  As vegetarians, my partner and I were so glad they had Impossible Burgers - which were cooked to perfection! After eating, we headed over to King's super-sleek bowling allies to burn off some calories (and drink their delicious mojitos 😉).  All-in-all, spending a couple hours at King's was super fun & super relaxing on a hot summer night. And totally affordable!  My partner and I left King's with huge smiles on our faces - and every intention of coming back.
Also, a special shout out to our super-polite servers: Brendan & Ashley. You guys were very awesome, thanks! 🙏

I'm familiar with Kings for their 20+ bowling lanes. But they also have an arcade room and decent-tasting food and drink. Everything is expensive but that's the norm in 2024.

Here's a pic of their bacon and bourbon burger. All burgers come with a side of waffle fries, yum!

I  ordered buffalo wontons and they were burnt. I’m only doing a review because I went and ordered right when they opened at 3pm I was literally the only person so I’m confused on why they are burnt ! I love buffalo wontons from here too ! The girl told me they had a big party to get ready for but that’s still no excuse plus I used to work at kings in Dedham so I already have an idea of how things shld b!

Lovely restaurant! Awesome lobster and services. Atmosphere is a bit bar-alike, not bad though but wasn’t something I expecting. Anyhow, I recommend Summer Shack! Price, taste and portion are absolutely great.

If I would have known sooner, this would have been my first stop while here in Boston!! The food, service, vibe… all great!
We had the lobster roll.. very good, although I do wish I could return for the warm butter lobster roll 😊. The oysters were so fresh and delicious.

When I return, I’ll Be Back at Summer Shack.

We were in town for a public media conference and wanted to go out to lunch with a client and friend of ours. Our friend enjoyed the lobster roll while my partner and I shared the Wood Grilled Lobster with garlic, parsley & buttered crumbs. The service was excellent. The food was wonderful. The location was convenient and we even got to sit next to the lobster tank.

Found this gem when dropping my daughter off at college. We ate there 2x in 3 days. We had fresh oysters there were absolutely amazing followed by their warm lobster rolls and a fun cocktail for two. At my 2nd visit I had a glass of Pinot, the lobster roll (again) and their tomato, basil, and mozzarella salad. The salad was delicious too!

The ambience is fun, we sat at a table at our first visit. Service was excellent, quick and very attentive. At my second visit I ate at the bar so I could watch the Red Sox game - the bartender was such a nice guy and also provided excellent service. We will definitely be back, i hear their poke bowl is “dope”.

I was there recently for a quick bite on the annual Boston Marathon day.  Looking for a casual but good seafood place, I stumbled upon this restaurant, and was very pleasantly surprised.

I expected a run of the mill menu, with some seafood dishes scattered among the regular bar food cuisine.  However, not only did I find a very decent selection of seafood, the quality surpassed my expectations.  Starting with the mouth watering Crab Cake appetizer, the absolutely delicious and flavorful Bouillabaisse (with a very hearty sauce and a generous amount of shrimp and mussels) for the main course, and finally to the biggest surprise, one of the best Pecan Pies for dessert, I could not have been more satisfied.  Sitting at the bar and having this great food was an additional treat, as the staff is very friendly and relaxed, and the ambiance very inviting and warm.

It was a great decision on my part to walk into this place on a whim, but it will definitely be a place I will return to.  If you happen to be in the area and want a lively, good seafood experience, with very reasonable prices, this is a great choice.

ChIJvVILJW1644kR9yD6YaMKlVA.name: Mela Modern Indian Cuisine
ChIJvVILJW1644kR9yD6YaMKlVA.address: 578 Tremont St suite1, Boston, MA 02118, USA

reviews.text:
We were looking for a quick dinner after arriving  at Logan airport from a long trip, we found this gem. We didn't have a reservation, were seated right away but we definitely recommended it.

As soon as I opened the door, the aroma from all the spices were incredible. The food was incredible, service was very prompt. The lamb coconut curry dish was amazing, it was nice and hot, the garlic and onion naan and the mango lassi were good. We were seated in front of the window and it was just a beautiful feeling. I would say it's a tight place but there is plenty of space, a very cozy restaurant, the chairs were a bit uncomfortable but suitable. The atmosphere was very peaceful, relaxing, everyone enjoying the moment.  I can't wait to come back.

Came back once again, did not disappoint me. I loved the service, the food was amazing.

Take out Chicken masala and a duck dish
Also added garlic naan
All was very delicious

This is definitely  a cute and cozy Indian restaurant in Tremont street. Delicious food and all ingredients are fresh and you can really get the fragnance of the fresh spices . This is only one of our fav Indian restaurant in Boston. I highly recommend this place if you in Tremont street and would like to taste a good Indian food !!

The chicken curry was all flooded in tomatoes. The palak paneer we ordered had a weird smell idk what. The food tasted real bad. Please do not try to sell people Indian cuisine if you do not know what Indian cuisine really is. Extremely dissatisfied with the food.

An unworthy place to visit. There's limited seating, and the buffet, priced at $20, offers a very small menu. All the curries taste the same with no distinct flavors. I recommend saving your time and finding a better option elsewhere.

Went on a Saturday for a Gergia Bulldawgs game with some friends. It was packed so service was pretty slow. One of the TVs had a horrible gren hue to it, one was running about 10 minutes behind of the others. Nothing tasted fresh, the fries were either frozen or had been sitting out for a while and were cold, but the seasoning was really good. Fish also had the texture of pre frozen fish but had a nice light batter. The nachos were very soggy by the time they got to the table and were not hot. Biggest issue was that in the women's room the locks DO NOT WORK. They unlock if someone turns the handle from the outside. Had to ask for water multiple times and at some point our server stopped showing up so we had to track them down. The hostess was leaning on the podium smacking gum with her mouth open.

I don't normally write bad reviews, but it felt like we were taken advantage of as out-of-towners. We didn't know that in MA you can't order a double (and our waitress clearly knew we weren't from there based on our IDs) and we ordered a double vodka redbull. Were scammed out of $30 for one drink. I know drinking in boston is super expensive, but that was insane! I was later told by a different bartender elsewhere that the only way they can "legally" serve a double is being charged 2 shots separately, and then were charged $8 for half a can of redbull. Absolutley insane. To add, our food was so-so, we had to go up to the bar to ask for silverware and napkins because we werent given any. basement is kind of cool. I feel like it would have been nice for her to warn us.  We probably would have ended up spending more money here because it could have been fun if this didn't happen.

Maybe we weren't taken advantage of and it was assumed we would know how much that would cost but a heads up would have been nice.

Had the cutest and sweetest waitress EVER. She was so kind and because it was my first time there, she helped me choose what to have for lunch. Went after pride month 2024 years with some friends and the atmosphere was very nice and everyone there greeted my friends and I with smiles and positivity. I think my waitress was Riley? Definitely would go again!!!!!!!!!!!!!

Clerys, located at 113 Dartmouth St, Boston, MA 02116, is a popular haunt for young professionals and college students alike,  just a stone's throw away from Back Bay Station. My alma mater hosted an event here before.

Overall Service: 3.34/5
Foods: 2.5/5, Service: 4/5, Ambiance: 3.5/5, Cleanliness: 3.5/5

With multiple bars, including a separate dance floor on the lower level, it can accommodate a sizeable crowd of up to 393 people (according to the staff). The place tends to get packed post-9pm on weekends, but it maintains a more relaxed vibe during weekdays. The friendly staff, especially the bartenders, add to the welcoming atmosphere. A tip: if you're yearning for a seat, scout the areas with large TVs; most patrons prefer to queue up for the dance floor.

When it comes to foods, unfortunately, Clerys didn't quite hit the mark here. The chicken wings, despite their reputation on the menu, were a disappointment. Overcooked and dry, they left my taste buds longing for more. The garlic parmesan sauce, too, fell short, barely coating the wings and leaving the flavor flat. Maybe it was my bad luck. A silver lining was found in the Bee Sting sauce, boasting hot honey, garlic, and red chili – a tantalizing combination. My wish is that they'd be more generous with the celery and carrot accompaniments given the portion size.

The potstickers, well, they were just okay, nothing that set them apart from your average Chinese takeout. On a brighter note, the cocktails at Clerys did manage to salvage our evening, offering a tasty respite.

Areas of improvements: (1) Clerys could benefit from some quality control in the kitchen to elevate their food offerings. (2) When the place gets crowded, the restroom can become less than appealing.

Not a terrible place. But if you’re not white just put some time aside to be treated as a second-class subhuman. Bartender will serve literally everyone else, have full fledged conversations, before casually turning their head to make a noise that you can only hope means it’s finally time for you ti get a drink. Btw…doesn’t matter what the bartenders background is. They act the same.

My wife and I reserved a table at this restaurant for our last night on our honeymoon. This was other worldly! Our waitstaff was very attentive! We were never out of water or wine. The meals were well paced and delicious. I don't often weigh the display of food as it comes out, but it is very obvious that the Mistral takes note in how each dish is staged before sending them out to customers.

Our appetizers were homey and a great wakeup to our pallets. The puff pastry texture and sweetness complimented the bisque beneath. The texture of the bisque was thinner than I would have imagined, but the texture and the flavor together worked well as an appetizer so that it wasn't too heavy to have before a main entrée.

I ordered the duck off of staff recommendation which came with a mushroom risotto and cranberry gastrique. Although plated together, there were very distinct flavors between each part of the meal. I would say this is the single most delicious meal I have ever had, and I don't say that lightly.

My wife ordered the salmon and enjoyed it (particularly the sauce gave an exciting and finishing flavor to the dish).

Our wine was great! (I've added a photo of the specific wine we had two bottles of)

The only thing I would say is that the dessert, while still good, was not up to par. After an amazing appetizer, entrée, and wine, I was a bit surprised to not be entirely wowed by the dessert. The staff did write congratulations on the plates as it was our honeymoon.

Overall, if you want to go somewhere on the fancier more expensive side, I'd say come to the Mistral if you want above and beyond service with great food.

Defintely one of the more higher end French cuisine restaurant in town. Doors open at 5:30 and when we walked in at 5:45, it was already half fully seated. Appetizers and main entrees were all well cooked, full of flavor. My favorite are the mushroom risotto in the half roasted duck and the tuna tartar. The bread 🍞 with homemade butter was delicious as well. The linguine was on the hard and chewy side, I was told that’s the more authentic Italian way to cook it. The knife used to cut into lamb can be sharpened, took some efforts to cut into it. Overall, nice vibe fancy restaurant for special occasions. Definitely not your everyday bistro.

Amazing as always! This is the third year in a row we've celebrated our anniversary here, and they always make it so special. The service is impeccable and the food and drinks are always fantastic. Highly recommend Mistral for your special night out!

I have dined at Mistral OVER 10x, there’s A LOT to say here so try to keep up. I can confidently say you can’t go wrong with anything on the menu—everything is exceptional. They do NOT skimp out on mussels. Every pizza is incredibly fresh, with house-made sauce and a perfectly crispy undercarriage. The duck is terrific and comes with delightful risotto, and the steak is a classic. Truffle fries can be a hit or miss, sometimes crispy, sometimes not. But the desserts? Absolutely insane. Honorable mentions to all gelato flavors and the torte. There’s a lot to love, so try to keep up!

Join me in tracking down the best bites!

I love the Mistral, it is my favorite restaurant in Boston. The service is always exceptional. Attention to detail is phenomenal, if you go to the bathroom they will tidy up your seat and even refold the table napkin. Plus, your water is always filled. They truly make you feel like VIP.

The waiter/waitress are always patient and will help you with any questions you may have. The food is amazing. The homemade bread and the butter are great. The sides that come with your entree always compliment/elevate the dish (no matter what you order). I always look forward to coming here and trying new dishes outside of my comfort zone because I know they have meticulously thought through the flavors.

ChIJS3rn5w1644kRfBOBxuHMxqg.name: Legal Sea Foods - Copley Place
ChIJS3rn5w1644kRfBOBxuHMxqg.address: Second Floor @ Copley Place Mall, 100 Huntington Ave, Boston, MA 02116, USA

reviews.text: So nice to have fried gluten free options! I had fried fish and shrimp (one at Copley place one and the airport). The shrimp was the best fried shrimp I’ve ever had. Would highly recommend! I tried to order a gluten free lobster roll but it was offered to me as a lettuce wrap (I think I understood they were out of bread)so I opted for fish & chips during that visit. Service was a little slow at Copley but the server was friendly. Service at the airport was super fast.

This was the very 1st restaurant we tried when arriving in Boston on Tuesday.  We ordered a few oysters a bowl of Clam Chowda which was excellent and we each got a Lobster roll, one with Mayo and one warm with butter.  Didn't realize how large they were and my husband and I split it to try each type.  It came with fries and coleslaw as well.  Our favorite between the 2 rolls was the warm by far. The cold one was a bit chewy and a couple pieces we weren't sure if they were fully cooked or not? Maybe the one with Mayo is supposed to be more chewy? We've never had a cold lobster roll. The hand cut steak fries were very good.  I did try the coleslaw and it seemed like it was just mixed with Mayo and didn't have much flavor at all.  My husband didn't even try his as he doesn't eat coleslaw out. He'll only eat mine that I make homemade. All in all this place was pretty good.

Plentiful seating and a vibrant atmosphere at this Legal seafood location. Everything we had was good, from the gigantic fish and chips to the clam chowder to the lobster bake. Nonetheless, the lobster roll was way overpriced at $43, especially when compared to stuffed lobster tails for $45. Service was good too.

They have some tasty food here. I tried the new ramen dish and it was delicious. The lobster mac and cheese my friend got was also pretty tasty. Gotta make reservations on the weekend. Not that stimulating as far as ambiance goes, but ut's a solid choice for family dining. Maybe not as a date in my opinion, but, whatever. It's a good restaurant.

Our company reserved the private room, but we had the stipulation that we needed to spend a minimum of $1,500.

We had 15 people attend, and after appetizers, drinks, and entrees, we still needed to spend $200. Luckily, desserts and multiple more drinks were enough to get us past the bill.

If I were to come again, I'd get the Lobster Mac N Cheese, not the Stuffed Lobster Tails.

Beautiful seating and ambience. Great for lunch and dinner. The service and food was excellent.
The bacon arrived a little overcooked and they replaced it immediately.

The croque Madame was very filling. Too heavy for me.

We prefer the malted Belgian waffle and french toast.

Nice French bistro vibe
The classic are there: Lyonnaise salad, steak frites, profiteroles and much more
Good choice and great flavours
Very nice service for such restaurants, way above what you can expect
A nice evening to spend with your partner or with some friends

Cute French bistro in South End with great ambiance, but overpriced dishes. The best dish was the bread pudding, it was crispy yet soft and moist inside, the warmth melting the vanilla ice cream on top. The steak was good but not thoroughly seasoned and not worth the price tag. Fries a little soggy. Duck was tender but the sauce was quite salty.

Had a fantastic dinner at Aquitaine on Tremont St. The mussels were fresh and flavorful, and the duck breast was perfectly cooked and paired nicely with the Chardonnay. Finished the meal with Calvados and an espresso – a perfect combo. Great French atmosphere

Typical Parisian bistro experience with great food and atmosphere.

For over two decades, Aquitaine has been offering a Parisian bistro experience in South End. Having enjoyed Chef Wood's other restaurants like Metropolis, I anticipated a similar quality at Aquitaine. True to form, the restaurant's interior, with its classic Parisian cafe vibes, burgundy couches, and tiled floors, set the perfect setting. During my recent visit on a weekday lunchtime, I found the place almost empty and was able to enjoy a leisurely meal.

Of the three dishes I ordered, my least favorite was the Escargots Bourguignon. Unfortunately, the escargot was pre-seasoned, which made it excessively salty rather than just lightly sprinkled with salt. However, the Sandwich au Canard was a redemption. It featured a superb blend of duck confit, pickled onion, and sweet cherry jam, all encased in heavily butter-toasted bread. The extra crunch from the bread not only added satisfying crunch but also intensified the umami flavors of the duck confit.

After the mixed experiences with the starter and the entrée, the Profiteroles Parisienne provided an excellent finale to the meal. It's one of my favorite ways to conclude a meal at a French restaurant, and these were on par with the best I’ve enjoyed at other French restaurants throughout the city.

Although the food at Aquitaine might not be as "innovative" as advertised on their website, it still provides an enjoyable traditional French dining experience, if you select the right dishes. I would definitely consider returning for dinner to explore more of their signature entrées.

Food is truly mediocre. Chicken Teriyaki was dry and bland. Also the rice tasted like leftover rice. The $45 sushi plate was so mid and not worth the money. The only thing that tasted great on the plate was the tuna. However, the crispy rice was the only thing on the plate that I would say was good. The sushi rice was served cold and was too big. Would probably try elsewhere for some good sushi.

My experience at Douzo was overall very enjoyable. The atmosphere was amazing, and the service was excellent—they even gave us a complimentary dessert to celebrate my girlfriend’s birthday, which was a nice touch! While the food was good, I do feel that it fell a bit short in terms of taste, especially considering the high price tag. That being said, the dining experience was still great, and I’d recommend Douzo for a special occasion or just a night out with friends or a significant other. It’s a great place to enjoy the ambiance and good company!

Visited this place 4 times in the 8 days that I was in Boston. The seafood is fresh and sweet. Staff are friendly and prompt with their services. Most importantly, this place had received the stamp of approval from my Japanese colleagues!

Modern chic ambiance compliments a delicious meal and tasteful cocktails. We had the shishito peppers, dumplings, and a couple of fresh sushi rolls for dinner. There are many interesting options - seems like you can’t go wrong. The pistachio dessert was a highlight and worth going back for.

This was my first "fancy" dinner in Boston after moving back. The service and vibes of the restaurant are absolutely fantastic. Just make sure you get a reservation, cause it gets busy!

We sat at the bar and the bartender was definitely nice, giving us solid recommendations and given us a show with different cocktails that were getting ordered.

Best dish of all time here though was the Uni Shot. We loved it so much, we got 3 orders of it! It's the right balance of umami, savory, and herbs all packed in a single shot.

We also got the Crispy Rice with spicy tuna. Great balance of crunchy and soft texture. I think next time, we're going to try it with the scallops. 100% would recommend ordering it again.

The octopus ceviche was perfectly prepared with a great balance of sweet, spicy, and freshness from the onions and cilantro. And the Tamari Scallops had a nice pop in your mouth if you enjoy a sour + slimy texture.

Sushi was incredibly fresh and tightly-rolled. We ordered the Douzo Special Roll, Sumo Roll, Mt. Fuji Roll, Backbay Roll, Spider Roll, Caterpillar Roll, and Volcano Roll. Would definitely recommend any of these again for next time.

Soft-Shell Crab was tasty but the only thing that would be a 3/5 since it was just a basic fried soft shell crab with tempera sauce. Would've loved a little bit more salt/pepper to bring out the briny-ness of the crab.

For Cocktails:
Death Jam (4/5) - nice balance of sweetness
Kabuchiko Martini (3/5) - definitely an interesting flavor to it, but probably wouldn't order it again

Overall: it's definitely on the pricey-er side, so great for special occasions or if I wanted to splurge for some solid sushi.

It was my first true seafood adventure, and I definitely picked the right spot! Cozy, upscale, comfy, and friendly vibes abound!! I tried clam chowder for the first time, and the flavors were exceptional. Truly, so so good. My waitress, April, was fully invested in my seafood journey and gave me fresh oyster to try. My mind was blown. I have clearly been missing out. Next came the lobster arancini - I wanted a slow intro to lobster - and YUM!! Paired with a glass of crisp bubble, these dishes were more than I bargined for in the best way possible. I treated myself to the lemon tart with raspberry, and I died of tart happiness. 20/10 Would bring my humans here.

Possibly the best tasting raw oyster i’ve ever had! I did not try too many, but I wish i had more of raw rather than fried.

The soft shell crab BLT was a hefty meal on its own as well! fries were well cooked and the sandwich was perfectly balanced

What they charge for a lobster roll here is criminal for what was provided. A soggy bun with too much butter and rubbery scraps of lobster (no claw or tail meat to be seen). Fries were a bit soggy despite having come out of the fryer just moments before.

Chowder was ok and the salad was the bare minimum you’d expect to get for $19. Oysters were fresh and decently presented.

Overall a bit of a tourist trap, not sure how it makes it on the list of classic places to eat in Boston.

We were in town for a short stay and decided to try out B&G Oysters as we were craving some fresh seafood. It did not disappoint! The oysters, mussels, and calamari were all delicious and at *peak* freshness. In fact, we had mussels again at a different restaurant later in the day and immediately noticed the difference in quality. The service was incredible as well. It was a hot day so we sat inside, but their back patio is perfect for an intimate meal. I highly recommend stopping in at B&G when you're in the mood for fresh seafood!

Good! What is there to say? If you are looking for a good place to have dinner in the area, B&G Oysters is the place to be. Open kitchen concept to create a bigger space ambiance with slightly limited indoor seating.

Surprisingly there were quite a number of tables with kids too! The calamari — you can nevee go wrong with fried food, their raw oysters are amazing! Island Creek will always be the best tasting for me. The cocktail sauce they make is delicious with the oysters as well.

For entree the scallops were perfectly cooked, flavors and texture blended well in the dish. As for dessert, banana pudding is banana pudding— maybe also try the chocolate mousse and let me know!

Drinks we had the Bee’s Knees cocktail and 1 glass of 2022 Rose. It went perfectly with the apps. The only thing is that we were always asked if we’re done with our plate. Anyway—

Til next time! Maybe brunch!

Got a blat sandwich in the morning and it took about 15 minutes. Sandwich came out steaming hot, and overall the sandwich was decent.

After you wait a while, you wonder if they forgot your order or not. There's no real system or receipts.

Great place for Açai bowls in the Back Bay Station. Opens early. Easy to order from the menu. Good options for very healthy juices and if you need flowers, they sell flowers too!! This was the Martinez bowl. Tasted great.
Ordered a tuna sandwich and it took over 10 minutes to come out. Wasn’t worth the wait (or weight) as it was fairly bland. Service seems a bit disorganized and isn’t the friendliest.
Ratchet subway juice station with OUTRAGEOUS prices. 30 dollars for two shakes. Cashier lady needs a serious lesson in customer service and attitude adjustment. Juice not so good.

Amazing juices. I had #4 green juice (it was so good!) after a long weekend a much needed load of greens to my system came as a blessing.
Just a block from a hotel, the only thing I regret is not making more than once to this place.
Loved the Pan con lechón sandwich (similar to pork sliders but better) never had anything like this before! Also got the calentado breakfast and I am impressed to how closed you got to my Colombian roots with this!!
Oh well, bye Boston and Jugos. We will be back one day!!

Sorellina in Back Bay is a must-visit for anyone seeking an exceptional dining experience. The atmosphere is classy and inviting, making it the perfect backdrop for a memorable meal. The attention to detail from the wait staff is impressive; they ensure every need is met without being intrusive.

The food is where Sorellina truly shines. Each dish is flavor-packed and thoughtfully prepared, transporting diners to a happy place with every bite. I regret not asking more about the chef, as the culinary artistry deserves recognition. The warmth and comfort of the dishes reflect a deep understanding of flavors, making each course a delightful journey.

Whether you're celebrating a special occasion or simply looking for a remarkable meal, Sorellina delivers on all fronts. Don’t miss the chance to indulge in this culinary gem.

My husband and I celebrated our wedding anniversary there, and I must admit that it was the best place we've ever been for dinner, and that they welcomed us so well. the food is wonderful. We felt very special and loved, our waiter Sandra was very attentive and helpful. I highly recommend it, we'll be back again. I would like to thank the entire Sorellina team.

Amazing experience! Filet mignon and salmon were amazing and cooked perfectly, but the star of the show was the lobster gnocchi which was absolutely perfect and so tender. Service was exceptional and unforgettable. Also really loved the affogato for dessert and the truffles!! Definitely some of the best food in Boston
Service and food were excellent! We had a good time here. Mark our server was friendly and attentive. I would 100% come back if back in Boston.

Fabulous dinner! Sebastian was our server and he was attentive, personable and gave great recommendations! The lobster gnocchi was divine! This meal was definitely a highlight of our stay in Boston. Highly recommend!

This place is iconic Boston. Downstairs is casual, with a bar and dining room perfect for brunch or business. Upstairs is formal with a dining room overlooking Boston's Common. The menu is classic and consistently delicious. Always get the tartare, might be the best in the city.

Upscale French restaurant right next to Boston Gardens. We were celebrating a friend’s birthday and our waiter generously offered the whole table some bubbles.

We ordered Grand Plateau (their seafood tower) and charcuterie board for appetizers. The seafood tower is mid - came with 3 pieces of lobster, 6 cocktail shrimps, tuna tartar, and a couple of raw oysters, raw clams, and mussels. Lobster and shrimps were both on the tougher side. A couple of my friends had sandy oysters. The prosciutto was delicious, however I was disappointed it did not come with cheese.

I had the duck breast as my main. It’s a bit tough to chew on the fatty parts but the rest was smooth and really delicious! The crispy rice is disappointing since it was barely crispy. It tasted like they shaped risotto rice into a disc and lightly pan fried it. The corn and veggie medley was crunchy and not to my taste.

They have a cake cutting fee - 12 USD per plate!

Book at the bistro downstairs for the vibes. Best tuna nicoise salad hands down! The chocolate croissant was dense, buttery, and flaky all at once. We also really enjoyed the croque madame and the ricotta pancakes. Service was excellent! Go on a Saturday so you can walk the farmers market right across the street.

We had a very nice experience dining in Bistro Du Midi. First, the manager Alberto, found a perfect table for us in the terrace. The food, drinks and desserts were delicious and our server Diana gave us the best service ever. I really want to come back soon!

I came here for lunch, and got their 3 course lunch deal for $45. I started with the Cesar salad, I didn’t notice it has anchovies which I don’t like, otherwise the salad was good. Main entree, I ordered chicken pillard and it was fantastic. Very thinly sliced, breaded and fried; with arugula, tomato and some other veggies on top. Chicken is very juicy and tender, despite being super thinly sliced! I loved the taste. Presentation is great looking. For desert, I got the flan which is great compliment to the meal. You also get nice bread with olive oil and to snack on. I ordered a Manhattan for a drink and it was very good as well.

This was a very unexpected 💎.  My sister and I found this place just by luck.  I can tell it's amazing.  The drinks are on point.  The bar tender has some skill.  The food, just yum.  I am a sucker for sweet potato fries and these are 🤤. It's very low key. Great music and if you really want they have a ton of tvs you can watch something.  We will def be back for an early night 🍸

Late dinner, on a Thursday night. At 9PM all tables were occupied.  Luckily we were the last group to snag a table without having to wait.

I ordered the Beyond Burger, and it came with sweet potato fries. Our server was super sweet.

It would have been nice to get a refill on waters, but it's not a big deal.

Definitely recommend, come support your LGBTQIA+ local businesses! 🏳️‍🌈

Great place to enjoy weekend brunch (off menu) and a mimosa. Friendly service, large space, fun and cozy atmosphere. They have the main  restaurant, a small cabaret room, and a larger room for a variety of shows. Nice bar as well. Parking is metered. No one rushed us. Definitely would return
Very LGBT friendly atmosphere and experience along with great food quality

My partner and I stopped in for drinks and dinner and had a very pleasant experience. Staff was delightful and helpful. Food was great- recommend the fried calamari! Cocktails could’ve been a touch stronger.

Very busy place but no wonder as the food was really good and the service was great. I had the ‘chicken fried chicken’ which was really good, I’d never had anything like it. Great spot for some live sports and no-fuss bar food.

Let me be honest I have left the giving review industry a while ago, but I have been getting back on it because the reviews are very misleading half of the time.

When I got there, there was a group waiting for me. It was a small Meetup that I believe happened before in that location. To my surprise when I walked in, it was really loud inside, often times on a summer night you expect noisy restaurants. What really bothered me was that me and my friend walked in and the only person who was welcoming was one girl who had a black hair.

My friend and I, we sat , about 20 minutes later not one person came by to check on us. See if we needed anything. At that point, there were seven of us seated on a table of 10 or so. My friend waved to a waiter so she can get services, the waiter, dead, looking in our eyes, then looked down and said nothing. Went back into the kitchen as if we did not exist.

I took it upon myself to go to one of the bartenders, the bartender was really nice and said they would send somebody to help us. After someone finally came to our table and took some orders, they took the first five orders and completely skipped over the rest of us.

Since this was a meet up, we were all going to pay separately. When we were ready to pay, the lady who was serving us, told us that we can only split the bill into two. Mind you everybody had their own way of paying some from cash other from card and etc.

The lady who was serving us also seemed very in a rush to stop helping us. Maybe I was the only one picking up on that. Anyway, one of our colleagues ordered the mashed potato and another one ordered the macaroni and cheese, they looked good and received good reviews from our colleagues. But the service was just really not it.

We all tried to have one person pay and then send that person either Cash app or give them cash for their trouble.

A few advice :

1. If you see a large group come in warn them that they can split the bill into two because some people don’t have that much money on their card. We are not living in Malibu, we are in Massachusetts. Warn.

2. Maybe checking on anybody within 10 minutes of them seating. We got water after I asked to have someone help us over 40 minutes into sitting.

3. Even if someone is not serving a specific table, you can hear what the people need until their actual waiter. Hey, go check on your people. Instead of being rude and walking away as we’re not trying to have a conversation or finding someone to help us.

4. Please put the volume down. We were screaming over ourselves.

5. I don’t know if this was a typo, the chicken fried chicken is very questionable as a title without actually including chicken in the ingredient list.

I give these reviews not to be mean, but to share my honest experience. This kind of felt like I was at rock-bottom. Majority of my party ended up going to another restaurant nearby. As much as it did not have the selections that we wanted from there, we enjoyed the atmosphere, and more importantly, the service.

It is packed every weekend, food is good, service is little late, staff looks careless but it is really busy and we respect that, they’re doing their best, it is entertaining, good music, good beer, fun atmosphere and I love this place

Inviting staff, and Robb was very knowledgeable on their beer recommendations. We had planned to bar hop all night but loved the atmosphere and the food, so we decided to keep it here for the evening..Don’t come here without trying the Kolsh and the Cider. Couldn’t photo the food fast enough, it was that good!

Stopped by for some great brews and food.  Pictures some happy hour Bavarian pretzels.  I ate one already and I am enjoying the Baltic Porter beer 10% abv.  Great night with music and TVs with preseason football and the Olympics.  Happy trails.

Easy to see on the corner of Church Street.   Tight space inside.   Due to its popularity from social media, the line is always long and goes down a small staircase.   The ingredients are sourced locally and you can taste the difference.   The Baller & The Crack were great tasting.    Are they worth a 25 minute wait?   That’s up to you.   Reasonably priced.   Moderately clean facilities.   Give this place a try if you’re in the mood for a new adventure.

Ok this place is a hidden gem located on the corner of a neighborhood street. I ordered ahead of time and had the Fancy breakfast sandwich, yummy. I upgraded to the sourdough and was pleased with that critical decision.. a tad pricey for a take out breakfast sandwich but I will certainly be going back.

I adore this place! It's the perfect spot to grab a bite and kickstart your day. Initially, I hesitated due to some reviews mentioning unfriendly staff, but I'm glad I overlooked them. The team here is incredibly friendly and professional. Now, let's talk about the food—those sandwiches are out of this world! The Fancy is my top pick, and the Breakfast Grilled Crack is also fantastic. Don't miss out on their delicious juices too. It's worth noting that the place is quite small, with only 3 or 4 stools for seating, so most people opt for takeout. Count me in for a return visit! Plus, they accept credit cards for added convenience.

Crazy delicious! This is the best sandwich I’ve ever had so far!!!

I ordered the breakfast grilled crack. Yessss nothing better than cheese and bacon combined together. They worked really well organized and good at cooking. There are some seats in the shop, but just a few. I recommend ordering takeout, it would be easier 👍

The guys working were phenomenal and the friendliest people we experienced at any Boston restaurant! Amazing food and very reasonable prices, the breakfast sandwiches were some of the best my wife and I have ever had in our life and we are from Dallas. Would recommend to anyone and will definitely go back every time we’re in Boston!

I had go with 3 out 5 stars because of the food. 😔
The corn-beef that was used for the Reuben Sandwich was not a good cut.aybe it was the end piece because It was tough. And unfortunately, the tuna melt, although looked good, did not taste good. The Coleslaw that I ordered with it helped offset the taste.
The service was great though! My husband had a Cafe Latte w/ almond milk..that was good.

Food was excellent. Only small issue was the size of the chicken in the chicken sandwich, as well as the size of the bowl with the chili. Definitely could be bigger given the price.

Other than that, the taste of the food, the overall atmosphere, and the service were great. Looking forward to my next visit.

Exactly what we were looking for! Casual diner with expected and unique dishes for my breakfast and friend's lunch. Good/not bitter coffee. Greenery Eggs Benedict was as unexpected as it was delicious. Not fancy, just great ingredients.  Floor to ceiling open doors let us enjoy the breeze.

AMAZING mediterranean food. Honestly, mediterranean prices too. As a greek myself I really appreciated the authenticity of the breakfast platter. Asked later, place is owned by a Turkish guy. Willing to put our differences aside and come back to enjoy another delicious brunch fs.
Visited for breakfast. Large selection on the menu.  Everyone was friendly.  Food tastes great and prices were reasonable.  Highly recommend!

Love this pub/tavern! Absolute gem with delicious food, a full bar, including beer tap and wine. The service was excellent! The bartender was friendly and knowledgeable  and had a Boston charm. I enjoyed the chicken, Caesar wrap and wine. Next time I’ll definitely come for an ale. Great atmosphere, great food, great service, the perfect combination!
We liked this place, the staff were lovely and we had a couple of goes on the wheel, didn't really like the drinks we won but it was a good laugh, would definitely go back

Bukowski’s is a classic “Dive Bar” in Boston’s Back Bay.  50 Dalton Street, across from the Prudential Center/Hynes Convention Center.  Best tasting cheese burgers and fries around for little dinero.  So, if you love Rock N’ Roll and other Poets, living or dead?  Bukowski’s is a must experience.

If you're looking for a simple and easy spot to grab a drink and a bite to eat, this place is for you. I've been here a couple of times after wandering Newbury street for the day and still haven't been disappointed. I loved their bratwurst and their rotating beers are always well picked. I can tell whoever selects them loves beer, which believe it or not is a very important thing to have in this type of place. Will be back!
Little hidden gem for a drink. Never had the   food. Character galore. Yes, the music is loud, but this is not the space for your most intimate conversations! Fun beer list.

ChIJb8BV9XZ644kRk542Fx092xg.name: P.F. Chang's
ChIJb8BV9XZ644kRk542Fx092xg.address: 8 Park Plaza Space D-6 Spc D-6, Boston, MA 02116, USA

reviews.text:
The restaurant is located in the busy Boston Commons area, where parking is very difficult. There is a garage, but parking for the duration of a meal costs around $20+.

The restaurant’s decor is very distinctive, featuring contemporary Chinese art. I particularly liked the dragon emblem in the men's restroom—it’s very cool.

The waitstaff are clearly well-trained and you can feel their professionalism. However, they seemed more trained than genuinely caring about the customers. For instance, we were seated next to a door that leads to the outside seating area. The servers frequently passed through it, causing strong drafts that made us uncomfortable. The restaurant was less than 50% full at the time, so we could have been seated at a more sheltered table.

The quality of the dishes is consistent with other PF Chang’s locations—very reliable. My favorites, the crispy fried green beans and chicken lettuce wraps, were as delicious as ever. The portions of the main courses were a bit small. The pepper steak, mapo tofu, and shrimp with lobster sauce were decent but not outstanding. Notably, the shrimp in the shrimp dish were smaller than those typically found in other Chinese restaurants.

In conclusion, I wouldn’t choose to come back voluntarily.

Currently, the restaurant offers a $12.99 lunch special, which is economical and worth considering.
One of my favourite chains.  Had my usual orange chicken but it appears the recipe has changed and it's more chilli than orange now.  Still an enjoyable meal.

A luxurious Chinese restaurant right in the middle of the downtown in Boston. It's located by Boston common and Public Garden - great for a group of people looking for some cool Asian food after all the activities around the area. Especially recommend for parents as they have good kids menus. Foods were neat and tasty served with good portion to share by plates. Liked their interior design being exotic and artistic. Seats were spacious and comfortable. Outdoor seating was available. Servers were kind and friendly. Nearby parking is very limited; some may be available along the Charles St. But recommend using the Boston Common garage.
Lovely experience! Our waiter David was absolutely amazing. The crab wontons and the changs spicy chicken was solid. The strawberry cucumber limeade and the cheesecake surprised me as well!

The food was excellent.  I spilled the hot and sour soup all over myself. The waitress came over and didn't seem concerned at all. She just said, yeah, the soup is hot. Literally nothing else. It took 2 requests for napkins and she did absolutely nothing to help clean up or take the aforementioned napkins we used to clean up. We had to ask for more soup as well. When we ordered, my husband asked what the rice options were for the meal we were ordering. She said brown, white and fried. He asked for the fried. She didn't tell us that there was a $4 up charge for the fried rice. We only noticed when we got the bill. She just kind of disappeared after the soup incident. Someone else brought our food out. She didn't come back to check on us until we were done and ready to leave.

The food was delicious though so that helped. Overall, not the best experience.  Definitely won't be going back to that one, but glad there are others we can visit because the food really was great.

Overall great experience here. The food was delicious, but the portion of fish for the fish & chips was small. The soda machine was broken and the beer we ordered was out, but  the food we ordered came out pretty quickly and tasted great. We had the cauliflower and steak appetizers, the cheese pizza, and the fish & chips.

A very busy and fun atmosphere bar in Back Bay. We opted to make reservations online (Resy) to secure an outside patio table on a busy Saturday evening. The place was packed, service was good and food decent. One chicken sandwich was a bit overdone, but quickly corrected by an excellent server and the lobster roll was outstanding.
The food was good and the service was on point. I had the fish & chips and would definitely have it again. The clam chowder was good.

The foods and drinks were good 4/5. But one of the servers was very rude and that ruined the whole experience.

Our main server was a very nice lady. But it was busy so it’s hard to get the server’s attention when we needed to order so we had to go through the hostess (the only person that walked by us)

We ordered dessert. Waited 30mins until we could not wait anymore so we told the hostess that we want to cancel dessert and just get the bill. The main server came, who had no idea that dessert never came out so she went back in to check.
Then a different server brought out the dessert, put at the edge of the table aggressively and said with an attitude “if it’s here it’s here”
I understand that it’s busy there. But that attitude is just not acceptable.

The manager refunded the dessert (we never touched). And we still tipped 20%, but I’m definitely not coming back.
Outdoor patio was an incredible atmosphere on a quiet Sunday. Got drinks from different alcohol groups and all were tremendous. Maria our waitress was very nice, and conscientious.

Cool shop, thank goodness.  The food was almost good.  The eggs had shells in them, the steak was overcooked and super salty.  The potatoes had perfect flavor but were mushy.  The cold brew coffee was not strong at all.  The atmosphere was awesome.  The concept is really neat.

Great cafe and bookshop with lots of good seating options indoors and outside including a big room upstairs. Excellent location in Newbury St. I love the home made corned beef hash & eggs and the trident bowl is delicious. Servers are friendly and super helpful. Recommended for breakfast and brunch!

Passed this place numerous times and I should have went in a lot earlier! Cozy and relaxed vibe. There’s a QR code on the table which you can purchase your order via the website. Dishes came out ~10 minutes later. Home fries were delicious and the menu offers a variety of options.

The bookstore is big and offers lots of books. Can’t wait to go back!

For the past ten years I’ve lived in Boston, Trident has often been my go to response for my favorite breakfast place in Boston. As I’ve been trying and reviewing a bunch of (to me) new breakfast places around town it occurred to me it’d probably been two years since I’d eaten at Trident and so I was curious coming back to see if my memory was clouded by nostalgia or if it still remained at the top of my breakfast list.

Spoiler alert: I still think it’s the best breakfast in Boston.

I ordered the corned beef hash which came with two eggs on top (I ordered mine over easy) and four slices of toast (they had a large selection and I got the sourdough rye which is a combination of my two favorite kinds of bread). I also ordered the loaded tots, and a “chaider”.

The corned beef hash is freshly made a just absolutely delicious. It incorporates more vegetables than one might expect: celery, carrots, cabbage, but I welcomed their inclusion. It made the hash tastier and more of a complete meal. I can think of only one other hash I’ve eaten in my life that I’d put above it at that’s at a diner in Colorado. Sincerely, the hash is wonderful.

The tots were good. I think they’re about as good as you can do with the concept, though if you want something similar but much better I’d recommend the latkas at Zaftigs. But still they were delicious and felt decadent.

As much as I loved my main meal the highlight was the “chai”-der. I believe it’s essentially a chai latte but made with cider instead of milk. It. Was. Amazing. One of the best beverages I’ve ever poured down my gullet. I need to remember they have it so I can stop in whenever I’m near Hynes. The combination of chai spices, and cinnamon, and rich cider flavor. It was as like a spicy hot cider and if that doesn’t sound like heaven to you, then I pity your poor tastebuds. I should have ordered a second to go.

I originally was going to eat inside but it was fairly crowded and it was a pleasant morning and nobody was sitting outside so I opted for that. You order virtually through a QR code at each table. You also pay first which felt weird to me. What if you want desert? I’m paying the tip before getting the service? I recognize that this was a covid issue, but it did feel a bit backward. If it had been done in a regular way then I WOULD have ordered a second chaider.

One last thing, and I’m not blaming the business as they had several wasp traps decorating the walls of the outdoor seating area, but eating outside mid-September I was besieged by wasps throughout my meal. Not to a horrific extent but enough to annoy me and if you’re phobic of those pests then I advise eating inside.

And one last thing: this is definitely a pricy breakfast option. For me it was worth it, but it felt extremely indulgent and it’s not someplace I could afford to eat at regularly. But for when you’re hankering for one of the best breakfasts available in Boston, it’s my go to pick.

Easily one of the best local bookstores I've been to in a long time! The front desk at my hotel recommended it as a great place to find a gift and I found exactly what I was looking for. I browsed the shop for over an hour, love it!

Busy venue but we had a reservation on Saturday night. Good service and acceptable prices on an eclectic menu. We enjoyed the Caesar salad which was substantial. For entrees we selected pepperoni pizza, shrimp scampi and pasta Bolognese. All were delicious. Full bar and wine list available, desserts and small plates to share. Service was good and the bustling atmosphere was okay ( you could still carry on a conversation).  We had a pleasant experience.

It was just okay. You’d think food places on Newbury Street would be memorable and delicious . Especially for the price. I’ve eaten at less expensive places with better food.

I asked for medium rare and received what looks like almost rare. Cooking for another 1-2 minutes would’ve made it perfect. It was so chewy.

The seating was very tight. We seated facing the street. Very close to the people next to us and in front of us.

Restrooms were in lower floor so would be tricky for anyone who can’t manage stairs.

Today was my second time back and it was just as incredible as the first time. Had the same wonderful waitress- Michalah T - who was very attentive and quick with everything. The salmon Caesar salad is by far the best I’ve ever had. I can say the salmon itself is the best salmon I’ve ever had as well. Tried a local beer this time (Jacks Abby House Lager) and that was excellent as well. Will definitely be back and would HIGHLY HIGHLY recommend. The calamari is also incredible!

We had our first date after becoming official at Sonsie and had a great experience (and obviously our relationship worked out!) so decided to celebrate our wedding here as well!

It was an exceptional experience working with Sari, the events coordinator, and the night went perfectly. Communication and collaboration through the planning process were very easy and a delight throughout. We really appreciated the thought and care she put into making our day special, from printing out and framing welcome and table signs to saving the rest of the cake in the fridge after the wedding so we could take it home the next day to enjoy. And when I went to pick it up the next day, I had forgotten to take a menu the night of but the manager kindly printed out another copy for our keepsakes.

The food was superbly seasoned and portions generous. The eggplant meatballs were a standout appetizer and the little gem salad was also very tasty! My salmon entree was nice and hot, with decadent crispy skin. It can be tough to maintain the quality when serving many people, but they did an amazing job! They also made special other dishes to accommodate dietary restrictions.

The wine room was a very intimate and lovely venue. All the guests complimented the food and the whole evening.

Thank you to Sari and the whole team. Would highly recommend for a night out or any special event!
We came here after 9pm, not so busy and was able to have a table right away. The waiter was friendly but he forgot my beer for long time. But foods were delicious.

ChIJi8WmgQt644kR4_Dbx1l7tT0.name: Thai Basil
ChIJi8WmgQt644kR4_Dbx1l7tT0.address: 132 Newbury St ste B, Boston, MA 02116, USA

reviews.text:
So I’ve been going to this restaurant for years. It’s very close to the Copley branch of the library and so conveniently located and just a super reliable spot for lunch. Probably my default option when I’m looking for something near Copley.

Today I had the spicy tofu lunch special which came with some small pork dumplings (I could have had spring rolls instead). The flavor of my meal was spot on, just the way I like it. Tofu wasn’t great by themselves but the flavor was there. Dumplings were also just fine. From prior experience I would recommend the basil fried rice and they have this eggplant thing which I think is my favorite thing I’ve tried there. Also the fresh Basil rolls are also really good.

I will say, it’s extremely standard Thai food and I don’t think it cracks my top three Thai restaurants around boston, but it is tasty, reasonably priced, and great location. I’ve probably eaten there close to twenty times. For me it’s a comfort lunch at this point.

We ordered the Combo Platter and Shumai to try a variety of dishes, and everything was delicious. The service and ambiance were decent as well. However, the space between tables was a bit awkward. We had a middle table for two, and with the place being so busy, the tables were uncomfortably close, making it feel crowded.

Cozy restaurant with delicious food! Service was great!
Highly recommend for their vegan options!
They were happy to customize the food per our dietary needs.

Great and calm atmosphere. Nice and friendly staff. I had a tom yum shrimp soup and it was pretty good, I liked that it was medium spicy. The salad was way to spicy I could barely eat it. The portions are good and prices are fair. Overall everything else was very good.

The red curry was a little dry for our taste, a little more sauce would have been nice. The crispy Pad Thai with peanut sauce was good. The prices were fair, especially considering the place is on Newbury Street.

The atmosphere here was so nice!! They were able to seat a table of 10 for us last minute. They have non-alcoholic drinks and a lot of variety in their food. Very authentic Italian sauce said my Italian teammate on par with his Italian grandma. The asparagus was my favorite! A MUST TRY, the asparagus.

My friends and I had the pleasure of dining at the Basile Fine Italian Kitchen on Saturday, 10/26.  The atmosphere and decor of the interior and exterior of the restaurant are amazing.  Our server that day was Joshua.  He was very pleasant,  courteous, and attentive to our requests.  He is very skilled at his profession and is a definite asset to Basile.  Myself and my friends enjoyed our meals heartily.  I chose the pumpkin ravioli, which I highly recommend.  In summary, I recommend Basile as a must stop for lunch or dinner when you are visiting Boston.

This restaurant did a poor job understanding the needs of one of our party members who adheres to a gluten-free diet. We assumed the waitstaff would be familiar in knowing the menu's gluten-free items because we saw gluten-free options on the menu.

However, when we wanted to confirm that the Gnocchi con Truffle was truly gluten-free, our waiter checked with the chef and told us it wasn't gluten-free.

Why is the gnocchi marked on the menu as gluten-free if it isn't? Our gluten-free guest was looking forward to enjoying that dish, but had to substitute with a plain tomato-sauce gluten-free pasta instead.

We appreciated that our waiter checked with the chef about the gluten-free status of the dishes we ordered, but it's disappointing to see something marked on the menu as gluten-free when it actually isn't.

There was also a long wait for our entrees, so service was much slower than we've experienced at other restaurants at a similar price point.

Overall, I don't recommend this place and I think you can get a better experience at other similarly priced restaurants.
This place was very nice 👍🏼 quiet and relaxing food was amazing we had the pasta Bella mare delicious!! We also had the calamari  it was amazing 😋

Our recent trip to Basile restaurant was awesome! The vibe was super romantic, with cozy setups, great tunes, and those cool candlelit tables. We were stoked to see the wide range of dishes and wines they had. And even though we're pretty picky about our wine, our server totally nailed it with their recommendations.The wine they suggested with our fish dish was spot-on, making the whole meal feel extra fancy. Oh, and the sea bass? So tender and tasty! Can't wait to go back for another round soon!

My friend and I headed to Boston to visit a good buddy, and we said ‘Pick the best sushi restaurant you can find’. We maybe should have said ‘but let us know what it costs’?

Ending up at Oishii was the best outcome possible when it came to the food, the ambience, the service, and just overall experience. I kid about the price - yes, it’s expensive - but I don’t know that you’ll find a cooler sushi spot anywhere in New England. The restaurant was busy on a Saturday night, and every table was packed with people having a great time. Date nights, large groups of friends - the energy was electric.

The presentation of the dishes alone was worth the trip, and the food lived up to everything else going on around it. If you want to splurge with no regrets - get yourself a table at Oishii.
Love coming to Oishii for our special occasion dinners. We love the Salmon On Fire, Wagyu, and Uni Pasta.

The food we was phenomenal. One of the best Japanese restaurants we had for sure. We had Wagyu Beef Tartare, 20 pieces sashimi, and the coconut sphere for dessert. We started out with a "sphere" in appetizer and ended up with a "sphere" in the desert. Everything was so tasty and "oishi" 😉. The coco sphere was out of this world and yumy (never had anything like that before), just right, not too sweet. Still wondering how they made it. The waiter was nice and fun but the 2 bus persons were a bit odd, in a hurry to take the plates from us. Their restroom door male and female label cracked me up and got me confused for a bit.

Okay, this was entirely my fault. I got a little carried away by what I “thought” was the newly improved restaurant scene in Boston after having a few excellent meals at Japanese Spots here. This was not one of those meals.

In my defense: I scoped Oishii out extensively online. Looked at many pics, read through multiple online versions of their menu (which were very misleading…).

Here’s the problem at Oishii: I’m going to go out on a limb and say that at least 90% of the menu items are deep fried/tempura. Not kidding. There is this huge, long sushi bar fully staffed with chefs and they’re deep frying every, damn thing. I’m sure that sells. It’s probably not a problem for them. Deep Fried sushi is not my thing and not why I came. So….my bad.

I had actually planned what I was going to order/eat from reading thoseonline menus. Pretty much none of the items I was planning to order actually appeared on the menu last night. I’m assuming they serve what sells for them: Tempura Everything. #eyeroll

The spot itself is very beautiful. Multiple levels, multiple bars and dining areas. Really lovely furnishings and serving plates, etc. Also? EXCELLENT Sake List. One of the best, most extensive I’ve ever seen. Super impressive. If they had had even just a “basic” sushi section on that menu Oishii might have worked for me. As in you can’t just order some ala carte pieces of sushi and/or some simple rolls. (I was not given a menu including that. I can see one online. Maybe I should have asked. I just assumed the fancy, bound menu they gave me was the entire menu??) You must choose from a large page of very elaborate rolls. I managed to find two that did not contain deep fried ingredients. And one of those was a California Roll.

Oishii is A Lot of Show and very little substance. Looks good. Decent vibe. Underwhelming food. What they’re serving is trying too hard. Everything is muddled. Too much tempura. Flavors and ingredients are not able to stand on their own.

On the upside: Portion size is ginormous. One roll will likely do you. So you could have a wonderful bottle of Sake and eat one giant Tempura something and be good!

What I had:

Cucumber Salad: EXCELLENT. Best thing I had. Led me to have irrationally high expectations.

Fried Vegetable Dumplings: really disappointing. Fast food type dumpling that was overcooked.

Spicy Salmon Crispy Rice: Very meh. I have no idea what was mixed in with the spicy salmon. But it was A LOT of stuff which made the entire piece too large. Almost impossible to eat. Which is a clear failure in the world of sushi. You must actually be able to get the piece into your mouth…

Scallop Crispy Shiso (I think this was on the appetizer menu): Okay, this was DELICIOUS. But this is also an entire meal. Tempura shiso leaf with a scallop on top and then piled high with shredded, fried Taro. This is one of dishes you can order with your excellent Sake and be one and done!

Mixed Green Salad: I needed to cleanse my palate from all the fried…basic salad. It was fine.

“Real” California Roll with King Crab. It was good. Basic. Fine.

For the Love of Salmon Roll: Tobiko, Avocado, Cucumber, Seared King Salmon, Ikura, Shiso, Spicy Mayo. Really good, gigantic roll. Very “busy.” Lots of things going on. Not usually my thing. But again, order one of these and you’re good!

I tried their “signature dessert” which is the definition of trying too hard. Hahahahahaha. So much going on. Presentation over substance. Cannot recommend. It’s something like a big, frozen coconut egg with some espresso mousse inside sitting in a little base of yuzu with some berries. #eyeroll

Nice Date Spot. If you live in the area also nice spot. Not worth making the effort to travel to.

I often come to the United States for business trips, but usually there is not much good food. However, this time is different. I particularly like their sushi because it tastes fresh and the sushi rice is very soft. The texture of the sashimi is soft and delicate. The decoration of the restaurant is full of elements of Japanese culture, and I recommend everyone to come.

Love the great selection of cheese and charcuterie here! Tons of other local products from bread to spreads available. Decent wine selection, specially for orange wine. Always a great joy getting recommendations of the lovely staff
It is like cheese heaven. So much to choose from. The employees are helpful. The quaint shop is what gives it its appeal; also the hand-written signange describing wach cheese's characteristic.

If you're ever looking for a reason why unfettered capitalism backed by monopolistic import laws and distributors is a terrible thing, visit this place.

$400 a kilo for pata negra, $200 a kilo for Salamanca, dry as a bone, sliced on a deli machine, and crushed between plastic sheets until it's a chunk you can wave around and smack your kids in the head with (see pic).

No cheese monger should slice jamon that expensive on a mechanical slicer.

$30 a pound of Bayley Hazen.

$20 for a handful of strawberries.

It actually makes sense to just fly to Europe, grab a few months of charcuterie, and fly back under the radar. It's basically like buying weed in Boston before 2016.

Never again.
Always a pleasure going there, trying great cheese, talking to super nice people and exploring interesting products from all over the world. Great selection of wine too!

Tiny, no parking, and pricey, but you can't get my favorite French olive oil anywhere else. Came out with the Mas de Bories grossane,  a bottle of basalmic, excellent parmesan, two kinds of olives, and a loaf of bread, too, so I guess I had a good time. Will be back.
The service was amazing. Staff were very nice. The food was also very good. The food was good. The eggs were very tasty. Would come here again.

Great service from both our waiters, feels homey inside and the food was excellent. We’ll be coming back tomorrow morning before we leave.

I had the steak & eggs with hash browns which were great. If I were to improve it, I’d make the meat a little bit more tender, it was slightly chewy. I’d use better quality eggs that have got a nice golden/orange yolk- but that’s just personal preference.

My partner had the French toast banana bread which was 10/10. Wouldn’t change anything about that. Really good.

I rarely leave food reviews but the service was great so I feel I had to!

Yummy diner experience with some awesome service (with a hint of diner attitude - in a good way).
Food was great and cheap.
Highly recommend if you're around.

The grilled banana bread was the highlight of breakfast. It has crispy edges and a wonderfully soft chew.

Charlie’s is hands down my favorite breakfast spot in Boston. The service was fantastic, coffee refills were fast, and everything was delicious.

Small, vintage diner specializing in breakfast items.

We traveled across Boston to visit and it was totally worth it. It was shortly before closing time but they seated us and said we could get take out if we took longer than 15 minutes to order.

Our food was delicious. One omelette set and one turkey hash set. They even made a new pot of coffee to fulfill my order.

Highly recommended for fans of diner food or vintage restaurants!

New owner in this Starbucks branch as he is very welcoming, nice and accommodating. I always order the same thing, so you can call me a regular. Walking in now he just knows my order and makes it. If not when I mobile order it's ready well before the time expected. The other staff as well, so nice and always smiling. The people here are always willing to give Pup cups to those with fur babies so make sure to bring them in for a treat. All in all, my place to come in and get coffee.
The ice lattes were great, it was incredibly packed, had to wait 15 minutes, felt like chaos.

I order the Iced Lavender Oatmilk Latte which had absolutely no LAVENDER in it! Was more of a green tea matcha & the person up front was very unpleasant heavyset sweaty and annoyed with life ! Which made me uncomfortable to even ask him to fix the order ! When paying the BUCKS @ Starbucks I should at-least receive what I want
Chain format has just gotten old and tired. Nowadays I always get a better experience and value from non-chain cafes. Starbucks has sadly joined McDonalds as boring tasteless plastic Americana

States here, on the door sign and the starbucks app that the store opens at 5:30am. My friend and I I tried to buy from there at 6:15am. The doors were locked, the staff inside did their best to ignore me. Starbucks what the hell, is communication of your operating hours not a priority. Or the money you save from having someone update times more important than the customers you loose who find another place thats open at 6:30am

L.A Burdick is undoubtedly the best places to enjoy the mouthwatering, super tasty and finger licking chocolates. I had a Milk Chocolate in a cold night of Boston, and it carved a unforgettable experience for me. I could feel the chocolate flowing through my throat and the taste could be felt even after an hour. I would definitely recommend this place to people finding a place to relax and have a sip of one of the finest chocolates in the city.

Kudos to the staff for this amazing experience.

A paradise for chocolate lovers! This spot offers an incredible variety of hot chocolates, from classic dark and milk to unique flavors like hazelnut and peppermint. Each cup is rich, creamy, and utterly satisfying.

But it doesn't stop there,  also boasts an impressive selection of chocolate sweets. From decadent truffles and luscious chocolate cakes to delicate chocolate-dipped fruits and handcrafted bonbons, there's something to delight every palate.

The cozy, inviting atmosphere makes it a perfect place to unwind and indulge. The staff are friendly and passionate about chocolate, always ready to help you choose the perfect treat. If you're a chocolate enthusiast, it is an absolute must-visit!

This place is so cute, we had meant to visit it before and finally got the chance it was close by our hotel this time.

The hot chocolate and coffee was awesome, the desserts, the ambiance, the service. Everything was so nice and pleasant.

The gentleman at the register was so diligent and polite wrapping our chocolate boxes to take back home as gifts.

A really nice experience. One we will remember, we will come back when we come back to Boston and we will.

Highly recommended!
Amazing selection of dark chocolate drinks and moccas. Cakes are great and finally in reasonable sizes. Good atmosphere, maybe just needs a little bit of music playing.
You can’t miss this place! One of the best chocolates! Each of their options has a unique flavor that will make your mouth water. Gluten free options are available but very limited.

Oh my gosh! What a wonderful dining experience! We couldn’t get into a Spanish restaurant on a Friday night, and randomly found Metropolis. Of course, we did not have a reservation, but the host was very kind. They took time and looked into their booking system, checking in with other staff and made us feel welcomed. They were accommodating and sat us at a bar. The bartender knew their drinks and food well. They were also very attentive to their guests’ needs. We enjoyed our food very much as they were fresh and tasty. Couldn’t have asked for a better meal on our last night in Boston! Highly recommended!!!

Good for brunch! I had the Smoke Salmon Eggs Benedict here and really was satisfied with it. The poach egg was perfectly cooked with great Hollandaise sauce, very creamy and went well with the toasted buns. Needed to wait for a bit too long, but it was busy hour so it was understandable.
Small, intimate atmosphere. Came here for brunch got the huevos rancheros with a buttermilk pancake. Everything was excellent. Service was fast, approachable. Food was well seasoned.

Went for an early dinner. Everything was teriffic and very reasonably priced. Holds up to 50 but was never noisy, unusual for S End. Music was nice and not loud. Attracts an older crowd who appreciates what it offers. Nice staff, too. Our  now favorite S End place. We'll be back.

Very cute and cozy, and we had great service. Loved the menu options and our drinks were great. We had the brussels sprouts, pork entree, and chicken mushroom risotto entree. The food was good, but could have been a bit better for the price. It was definitely a cute place for a date night overall, with a pretty convenient location.

Brunch was the meal I ate at the Boston. MA location.  The location is convenient because a parking lot is next door, and it is close to other shopping or experiences in the area.  Our server was great , she was pleasant, patient, and friendly.  The food was served hot, and it came as they were described on the menu.  The Check-out process was easy because the server has a handheld device to accept your card payment.  While the food was fresh, all but the egg sandwich lacked seasoning;  so it makes me wonder if this place only has a cook and not a chef cooking/supervising its preparation.  Most restaurants regardless of who is serving the customer make it so every server can respond to or follow-up when your assigned server is overwhelmed but at this place although I was waiving my hand to get the hostess attention she ignored me until I got up from my chair to ask for more napkins and my check.  Eventually, I got both, but the hostess appeared frustrated that I asked for this help.  If I had to eat here again, I would if I had to stay local, but I would go with the egg sandwich because that did have a flavor that my mouth enjoyed.

Had a delicious, impromptu,
solo brunch with Tori at the bar, great atmosphere. She was welcoming and so sweet! Everything was delicious and exactly what I was hoping for. I haven’t been here in a while (too long) but I definitely plan to be back!!

Brunch and dinner amazing! Always great vibes from the staff and music selection. The staff favorite for dinner is the Nashville hot cauliflower and for brunch the FCCFT or Aglio olio (hangover cure). Right next to back bay station for commuters. Go visit bartenders Emily and Lex!

Walked in for breakfast. I would give 3 stars if it wasnt for the waitress that was super friendly and did her best to accommodate our preference.
There was no salad on the menu not even a side salad, she told us they can bring one however we like it which was nice.
Other than that we both got the brownstone special plate. Eggs and potatoes were ok but bacon and sausage were incredibly greasy and bacon wasnt crispy, so soft…
Coffee was missing taste..
Would only go back there at night for drinks to try but never for brunch/breakfast.

This place is cute and elegant. The food choices and prices are well fitting. I like the atmosphere a lot. The waitress and staff are friendly and attentive. My steak was a little undercooked than what I asked for but it was still very delicious.

I recently had a wonderful dining experience at this charming restaurant in Boston with lovely outdoor seating that offers a great view of the bustling street. The atmosphere was perfect for enjoying a relaxing meal in the city.

The waitstaff were attentive and friendly, ensuring we had everything we needed throughout our meal. We started with some fresh bread served with olive oil, which was a simple yet delicious way to begin. For the main course, we ordered the black truffle mushroom pasta, which was rich and flavorful, paired with a fresh salad that balanced the meal perfectly.

One of the most creative touches was when I ordered a glass of wine, and it came with a thoughtful card detailing information about the wine. It made the experience feel even more special and personal. Overall, the food was excellent, the service impeccable, and the outdoor seating was a great spot to enjoy a meal with a view. Highly recommended!

Piattini is an absolute gem! The ambiance is cozy and welcoming, perfect for an intimate dinner or casual gathering with friends. The menu is full of delicious, authentic Italian dishes, and every plate is crafted with care and bursting with flavor.
The wine selection is impressive, and the staff is incredibly knowledgeable, helping you find the perfect pairing. Service is attentive and friendly without being intrusive. Highly recommend! Five stars!
The food and drinks were delicious. There is outdoor (at least in October) and indoor seating. The left and right sides of the indoor seating each have a different vibe, of which both are enjoyable.

Hostess was so friendly and accommodating our party’s sitting outdoor preference. The restaurant is just beautiful as there are three dining room options and an outdoor sitting area (one of the prettiest outdoor areas very quaint and cozy with lots of greenery/plants providing an intimate experience) as our family chose to sit as the weather was spectacular on a Sunday afternoon. We were greeted by our male server who provided Excellent customer service!! The food was absolutely delicious and good portions for the price. We would definitely return when in town!

The restaurant seating is cozy and the ambience is nice and has calm lighting. We arrived with 7 people and a reservation, with no issues. Our server was very kind and patient, and didn't rush us at all. Our food was delicious, and reasonably sized. Orders with individual items, like bread sticks, or the bruschetta, arrived with only 2 per order, so you may need to share, if you're going with more than one person.
